- Feedback saturation calls
    - format: one entry per chapter when first-pass extraction completes
    - entry shape:
        - what came out of this chapter
        - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - why those did not make it
        - decision: saturated | re-sweep needed

- Chapter 1: Front Matter (praise, title page, copyright, dedication, contents)
    - what came out: nothing
    - what didn't make the gate: not applicable. Bibliographic metadata, no teaching content.
    - why: structural front matter, not authorial argument or demonstration.
    - decision: saturated (vacuously, with zero skills)

- Chapter 2: Introduction (From Push to Pull)
    - what came out: three skills
        - pull-not-push-reroute: moment-to-moment application of the receiver-as-leverage reframing, used when the giver-inadequacy inventory is running.
        - engaging-is-not-accepting: separates the engage-skillfully decision from the take-the-feedback decision, dissolving the swallow-or-shut-out binary.
        - name-both-needs: names the simultaneous drives to learn and to be accepted as the diagnostic for outsized or delayed reactions.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - the broad definition of feedback (any information about yourself): parent-context framing, no distinct receiver-side action.
        - the brief mechanical-to-managerial history of "feedback": context, not procedure.
        - feedback-seeking behavior research: empirical motivation for the book; the actual seeking procedure lives in chapter 12 (Get Going).
        - modeling effect (kids, direct reports): stakes-raising frame, not a receiver move.
        - "digging for ponies" disposition: aphorism that points at "First Understand" (chapter 5) where the actual technique is taught.
        - the three triggers themselves: previewed only; the chapter that develops them is chapter 1 (Three Triggers That Block Feedback) where they get their own skills.
    - why those did not make it: most of the intro establishes the lens and vocabulary that already live in _book.md, or signposts later chapters where the actual procedures get developed. Pulling skills here would either duplicate parent context or pre-empt material the book itself defers.
    - decision: saturated (3 skills)

- Chapter 3: 1. Three Triggers That Block Feedback
    - what came out: one skill
        - identify-which-trigger-is-firing: the chapter's framework-level meta-move. When triggered by feedback, name which of truth/relationship/identity (or which mix) is firing before applying any remedy. Folds in the smoke-alarm framing (triggered reaction is a map, not just an obstacle), since reading the alarm and categorizing among the three is a single move.
    - what kinds of moves the chapter is about that did NOT make the gate
        - separate appreciation, coaching, evaluation: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 4.
        - first understand: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 5.
        - see your blind spots: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 6.
        - don't switchtrack (disentangle what from who): previewed here but is the spine of chapter 7.
        - identify the relationship system: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 8.
        - learn how wiring and temperament affect your story: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 9.
        - dismantle distortions: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 10.
        - cultivate a growth identity: previewed here but is the spine of chapter 11.
    - why those did not make it: chapter 1 is a synopsis chapter. Each remedy under the three triggers is the title of a chapter that follows, and the deep treatment (specific moves, signals, failure modes, scenarios) lives there. Promoting a half-developed version here would either pre-empt material the book itself defers, or force a duplicate skill when the dedicated chapter is reached. The skills system is better served by leaving each per-trigger remedy for its own chapter and extracting only what is genuinely born in this chapter: the framework-level diagnostic that names the trigger before selecting any remedy.
    - decision: saturated (1 skill)
